## Architectural Invariants

### Invariant 1 — Store Is the Single Source of Truth

All downstream phases (3–11) MUST read project state exclusively through `ProjectStateStore`. No downstream phase may import or call `GitLabFetcher` directly.

### Invariant 2 — Entity Immutability Preserved

Phase 0 domain models are `frozen=True`. Phase 2 never mutates Phase 0 domain models. Stored references are replaced with a fresh instance, whether newly mapped or created via `model.model_copy(update={...})`.

### Invariant 3 — Timestamp-Ordered Updates

When applying incremental webhook updates:
- If `payload.entity_updated_at is not None` AND `stored_entity exists` AND `payload.entity_updated_at <= stored_entity.updated_at`: discard, log DEBUG, return `UpdateResult(applied=False, reason="stale_event_discarded")`.
- If `payload.entity_updated_at is None`: skip the guard and apply the update.

### Invariant 4 — No Direct GitLab API Access

Phase 2 modules MUST NOT perform runtime imports from `gitlab/client`, `gitlab/fetchers`, `gitlab/rate_limiter`, `gitlab/retry`, or `gitlab/pagination`. Type-only imports guarded by `if TYPE_CHECKING:` are permitted for `GitLabFetcher` in `engines/state/manager.py` to support signature annotations. The only permitted runtime `gitlab/` import is `gitlab/webhooks` (for `WebhookPayload`, `WebhookEvent`, and `map_webhook_to_model`).

### Invariant 5 — Completeness Is Always Known and Always Honest

`StateMetadata.completeness` is always set. It must never be `FULL` unless a complete, uninterrupted full refresh completed with zero fetch failures and a non-None project entity. Only the full-refresh path may result in `FULL`, and in practice this is enforced by `StateManager.refresh_project()` using the normalizer's output.

