## Error Handling Philosophy

Carried forward from Phase 1. Fully in effect.

### The Hard Rule

**When in doubt: raise. It is always safer to surface an error loudly than to hide it quietly.**

### Fail-Fast Conditions for Phase 2

| Condition | Reason |
|---|---|
| Container accessed before `initialize()` | Programming error |
| `store.update_entity()` called for untracked project | State corruption risk |
| `StateManager` constructed without required dependencies | Invalid object state |
| `ProjectState` stored with mismatched `project_id` | Silent data corruption |
| Invariant 4 violated | Architectural contract broken |
| `normalize_project_data()` receives non-dict or empty input | Input contract violated |

### Fail-Soft Conditions for Phase 2

| Condition | Reason |
|---|---|
| One FetchResult with failures > 0 | Mark PARTIAL, continue |
| One entity fails relationship extraction | Other relationships still valid |
| One project fails in concurrent refresh | Other projects independent |
| Orphaned reference in ConsistencyChecker | Warning, not blocking |
| Webhook for untracked project | Return UpdateResult(applied=False) — not an error |

### Every Failure Must Produce Two Signals

1. A structured log entry at `WARNING` or `ERROR`.
2. A caller-visible signal — exception (fail-fast) or failure-tracking return type (fail-soft).

